<div id="banner">
	<h1>There&#8217;s Only One Way To Do It</h1>
</div>

<div class="content">
<p>To balance out the Perl I thought I&#8217;d share this quote. [<a href="http://www.ddj.com/documents/s=1712/ddj1029798360502/do200208py002.htm">PyURL</a>]</p>

<p>&#8220;I thought that it was a firm principle of language design&#8212;out of concern for programming as a human activity&#8212;that in all respects equivalent programs should have few possibilities for different representation [&#8230;]. Otherwise completely different styles of programming arise unnecessarily, thereby hampering maintainability, readability and what have you. This requires from the language designers the courage to make up their minds!&#8221;<br />
 - Edsger W. Dijkstra on GREEN, an early version of Ada</p>

<p>My personal goal when writing Python libraries is that the code one writes without looking at the documentation should work. Sadly, it seems few people understand the concept of ease-of-use when applied to libraries. Ken MacLeod is one of the few excellent library designers.</p>

<p class="posted">posted September 02, 2002 10:33 PM (<a class="category" href="http://www.aaronsw.com/weblog/cat_technology">Technology</a>)  <a href="000558" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>

